- AC/DC’s Who Made Who certainly satisfies my taste for punch, tight performances, concise song lengths, and preserved dynamics, but it is fundamentally a riff‑driven hard rock album whose strengths are guitar heft and a unified rock journey. Its vocal character (gritty, snarling delivery) and “raw‑but‑clear” production are stylistically different from the crystal‑clear, voice‑forward pop presentation I favor. It leans toward album‑length, riff‑forward engagement rather than the immediate, playlistable singles focus and sing‑along choruses that I prioritize. Because my stated dislikes include albums that aren’t forward‑vocal, or that reward intense analytical listening over casual replay, Who Made Who is less aligned with my primary aims.
- In short: the pop album aligns with the exact sonic and sequencing profile I asked for (lead vocals up front and pristine, punchy single‑style tracks with preserved dynamics), while AC/DC, despite being excellent rock production, emphasizes guitar‑driven texture and album cohesion over the crystal‑clear, studio‑polished vocal singles compilation I prefer—so I select the pop album and reject Who Made Who.

