The user updates his self-description as follows: I now favor slightly roomier, 80s‑tinged pop/soft‑rock production where lead vocals have emotional presence set a little back in tasteful room/reverb rather than hyper‑close miking. I like big, gated/ambient drums that still punch and breathe, warm midrange and piano/vintage keys for color, and lush but controlled arrangements that prioritize melodic clarity over clinical brightness. I still value concise, hook‑first AOR focus, tight melodic bass, transient‑preserving masters with generous headroom, tasteful tape warmth and compression that keeps micro‑dynamics and attack, restrained harmonies, and transparent stereo imaging. I dislike raw, underproduced thin mixes; over‑sparse arrangements lacking punch or emotional depth; excessive stacked harmonies or low‑mid muddiness that mask mids; over‑compression that destroys attack; and hyper‑bright, hyper‑close vocal mixes that feel clinical.

The positive CD has the following updated information: Roomy 80s AOR/soft‑rock: lead vocals placed slightly back in tasteful room/tape reverb, big gated ambient drums that punch and breathe, warm midrange piano/vintage keys, tight melodic bass, restrained harmonies, transparent mastering with headroom and transient‑preserving tape warmth.

